{
  "version": 1,
  "goals": {
    "ses_18d67301cffefhu80TOpQughxO": {
      "id": "5cbb5cca-4d37-4ed1-b898-faea4faf662f",
      "sessionID": "ses_18d67301cffefhu80TOpQughxO",
      "objective": "https://github.com/CVEProject/cvelistV5/tree/main make a plan for codex to make a website and mcp called semantic-cve The main goal will be to find out the CVEs based on the semantic search. You can use, you can create, the codex can create embeddings for each of them and regex search will also be available. Make sure that the list is cached and this cached list can be updated on daily basis. I don't know how semantic search works, so create a strong plan for both the website and MCP servers. use ts/ svelte/react and python for search/embeddings, prefer less/no python because vercel wont host python. also use local ollama qwen3-embedding:4b Binary question: Could hidden user memory that is not visible here materially change what I should recommend for this Semantic-CVE project (for example, prior architecture decisions, hosting constraints, MCP standards, or existing codebases)? (Yes/No) no Semantic-CVE A semantic vulnerability intelligence platform + MCP server that allows AI agents and humans to search CVEs using natural language instead of only CVE IDs or keywords. Example queries: Windows privilege escalation using symbolic links Apache authentication bypass in reverse proxy Python deserialization RCE recent auth bypass vulnerabilities with public exploits Returns: Relevant CVEs Similar vulnerabilities CWE information Affected products Severity References Semantic similarity score Tech Stack Frontend React + Next.js (App Router) Tailwind shadcn/ui TanStack Query Reason: Easy Vercel deployment Good SEO Fast search UI Backend Main API TypeScript Fastify Prisma PostgreSQL Search Service Python only for indexing. Runtime search: TypeScript Avoid Python server entirely. Embeddings Local: Ollama qwen3-embedding:4b Embedding generation runs during indexing. Architecture cvelistV5 │ ▼ Indexer │ ▼ PostgreSQL ├── CVE Metadata ├── References ├── CWE ├── Products └── Embeddings │ ▼ Search API │ ├── Semantic Search ├── Regex Search ├── Hybrid Search └── MCP Server │ ▼ Website Data Pipeline Initial Sync Clone: git clone https://github.com/CVEProject/cvelistV5 Parse every CVE JSON. Extract: { cveId, description, cwe, vendor, product, affectedVersions, cvss, references, datePublished, dateUpdated } Store in database. Embedding Text Create a normalized document: CVE-2025-1234 Description: Authentication bypass in Apache HTTP Server. Vendor: Apache Product: HTTP Server CWE: CWE-287 Severity: Critical Affected: 2.4.0 - 2.4.59 Generate embedding. Store vector. Database Postgres + pgvector Tables: cves embeddings cwes products references Search Modes 1 Semantic Search Query: windows kernel bug allowing admin access Workflow: query │ embedding │ pgvector similarity │ top matches Result: [ { cve :\"CVE-2025-XXXX\", score :0.92 } ] 2 Regex Search For power users. Examples: Apache.* .*deserialization.* Searches: descriptions vendor products 3 Full Text Search Postgres FTS. Example: nginx buffer overflow 4 Hybrid Search Best mode. final_score = semantic_score * 0.7 + fts_score * 0.3 Usually beats pure embeddings. Similar CVE Discovery Open CVE: CVE-2024-1234 Find nearest vectors. Returns: Related CVEs Useful for: threat hunting vulnerability research exploit development research MCP Server Tools search_cves Input { query :\"apache auth bypass\" } Returns: { results :[] } get_cve { id :\"CVE-2025-1234\" } related_cves { id :\"CVE-2025-1234\" } Uses vector similarity. regex_search { pattern :\"Apache.*\" } search_by_product { product :\"Apache HTTP Server\" } search_by_cwe { cwe :\"CWE-79\" } latest_cves { days :7 } search_exploit_like Natural language: { description :\"vulnerabilities that allow unauthenticated remote code execution\" } Semantic search. Website Home Single search bar. Examples below it: Search vulnerabilities naturally... Examples: Linux privilege escalation Recent RCEs Apache auth bypass JWT verification flaws Results Page Each card: CVE-XXXX Description CVSS Published Affected Products Similarity Score CVE Detail Page Sections: Overview Severity References CWE Products Similar CVEs Timeline Research View Advanced filters: Vendor Product CWE CVSS Year Published date AI Research View Prompt: Find authentication bypass vulnerabilities Returns grouped results. Categories: auth bypass RCE XSS SQLi LPE Generated through semantic clustering. Daily Updates Cron: daily Process: git pull Detect changed CVEs. Only re-index modified files. Incremental Updates Track: sha256(file) If changed: re-embed Else skip. This makes updates very fast. Performance Optimizations Cache Redis Cache: popular searches popular CVEs embedding queries Query Embedding Cache User query: apache auth bypass Embedding stored. Future searches avoid Ollama call. Future V2 Vulnerability Clusters Automatically group CVEs. Examples: Path Traversal Authentication Bypass Remote Code Execution using HDBSCAN. Exploit Links Ingest: ExploitDB GitHub PoCs Nuclei templates Link them to CVEs. Agent Mode MCP tool: { query :\"Find all Apache RCEs from last 2 years with CVSS > 9\" } LLM converts query into filters + semantic search. Codex Build Phases Phase 1 CVE parser PostgreSQL schema pgvector Initial import Phase 2 Ollama embedding generation Vector storage Semantic search Phase 3 MCP server search_cves get_cve related_cves Phase 4 Next.js website Search UI CVE pages Phase 5 Daily updater Incremental indexing Redis cache Phase 6 Hybrid ranking Similar CVEs Clustering Phase 7 Exploit intelligence Threat research tools The key design choice is: do not use a Python search server. Use Python only as an offline indexing utility if absolutely necessary. The production stack should be TypeScript + PostgreSQL pgvector + Ollama, which deploys cleanly on Vercel while keeping semantic search entirely local. no, minimal python or not at all Then I'd redesign it around a 100% TypeScript stack. Python adds deployment complexity, separate services, dependency hell, and doesn't buy much here. Semantic-CVE v2 Stack Frontend: Next.js React Tailwind shadcn Backend: Fastify TypeScript Database: PostgreSQL pgvector Embedding Model: Local Ollama qwen3-embedding:4b Hosting: Vercel (frontend) Small VPS (API + Postgres + Ollama) Core Idea Instead of: search query ↓ python ↓ vector db Do: search query ↓ typescript ↓ ollama embeddings ↓ pgvector Everything stays in Node. Monorepo semantic-cve/ apps/ ├─ web/ ├─ api/ ├─ mcp/ packages/ ├─ cve-parser/ ├─ embeddings/ ├─ search/ ├─ db/ ├─ shared/ scripts/ ├─ sync-cves.ts ├─ embed-cves.ts ├─ daily-update.ts No Python. Search Architecture Three independent search engines. Semantic query ↓ ollama embedding ↓ pgvector cosine search Fulltext Postgres tsvector. description vendor product cwe indexed. Regex Raw SQL regex. WHERE description ~* pattern Hybrid semantic score + fts score + exact match boosts Example: User: apache auth bypass Scoring: semantic 60% fts 30% vendor/product boost 10% Better Embedding Strategy Don't embed only descriptions. Create a synthetic document. CVE-2025-1234 Vendor: Apache Product: Apache HTTP Server Type: Authentication Bypass CWE: CWE-287 Description: ... Affected Versions: ... Then embed. Semantic search becomes dramatically better. Cache Strategy The repository is enormous. Never parse live. Build Cache cve-cache/ Contains: metadata.json embeddings.bin hashes.json Daily Update GitHub Action: git pull Detect changed files. new file modified file deleted file Only process deltas. Hash Based Updates SHA256(file) Store: { CVE-2025-1234 :\"abc123\" } If hash unchanged: skip If changed: reparse reembed update db MCP Design Keep MCP tiny. Tools: search_cves get_cve related_cves search_by_product search_by_cwe latest_cves Avoid dozens of tools. The MCP should behave like: semantic vulnerability database not SQL over MCP Website Features Search Google-like. Search vulnerabilities naturally... Result Cards Show: CVE CVSS Vendor Product Published Similarity CVE Page Tabs: Overview Affected Products References Related CVEs JSON Source Similar Vulnerabilities This becomes the killer feature. Open: CVE-2024-4577 See: 12 semantically similar vulnerabilities Researchers love this. Advanced Feature Instead of searching CVEs... Search intentions. Example: vulnerabilities that allow attackers to become admin after login Semantic search converts that into: Privilege Escalation Authorization Bypass ACL Issues and surfaces relevant CVEs. This is where embeddings become genuinely useful. Performance Goal Repository: ~300k+ CVEs eventually. Target: Top 20 semantic results <100ms using: pgvector HNSW indexes cached query embeddings hybrid ranking What I'd tell Codex to build Phase 1: CVE parser Postgres schema pgvector Phase 2: Ollama integration embedding generation vector search Phase 3: incremental updater hash tracking daily sync Phase 4: MCP server Phase 5: Next.js UI Phase 6: hybrid ranking similar CVEs query cache Phase 7: exploit intelligence clustering researcher features The strongest version of this project is not semantic search for CVEs. It's GitHub for vulnerability intelligence with semantic retrieval as the backend. The semantic layer should feel invisible; users should simply be able to describe a vulnerability in plain English and immediately discover related CVEs.",
